external_knowledge:
- "guardians of the realm" refers to the users in the system;
- "last known components they interacted with" refers to the components accessed most recently by each user;
- "dates of their most recent encounters" refers to the most recent `access_date` for each user.

- "Most recent access" refers to the latest date when a user accessed a component;
- "Access count" is the total number of times a user has accessed a component;
- "Component" is a part of a system or device;
- "Component type" refers to the category or category name of the component.

sql:
SELECT AVG(min_value) AS average_min_value, characteristic_type_id
FROM characteristics
GROUP BY characteristic_type_id;

external_knowledge:
- Components are categorized by their types;
- The latest revision date is the most recent date the component was updated;
- The results are grouped by both component name and type name to ensure unique entries for each component and type combination;
- The order is first by type name in ascending order and then by the latest revision date in descending order.

- "blossomed the most in terms of revisions" refers to components with the highest number of revisions;
- "pruned" refers to the revisions made to the components;
- "richness of their growth" refers to the count of revisions;
- "freshness of their last touch" refers to the latest revision date.

- 'Performance characteristics' refer to specific attributes or metrics that measure the performance or efficiency of a component;
- 'Average minimum and maximum values' of performance characteristics are calculated to provide a range within which the component typically operates;
- 'Access count' and 'average access date' provide insights into how frequently the component is used and when it is typically accessed.

- 'gardeners with administrative privileges' refers to users with the role 'admin';
- 'flowers' metaphorically represent components;
- 'visited' refers to the `access_date` indicating the times the components were accessed.

- "components" refer to individual parts or elements within a larger system;
- "categories" refer to the classification or grouping of these components;
- "fertile" is used metaphorically to describe categories that contain a high number of components.

- "blossoms" refer to the number of access events;
- "bloomed" refers to components that have been accessed more than 5 times;
- "garden of technology" is a metaphor for the database of components and their access logs.
